"Paradigms in pharmacology refer to the dominant conceptual frameworks, research approaches, and philosophical shifts that guide how the field studies drug actions, discovers new therapies, and applies knowledge. Like Thomas Kuhn's scientific paradigms, these evolve through periods of "normal science" punctuated by shifts driven by new technologies, failures of prior models, and integration of broader biological understanding. 
en.wikipedia.org

Historical and Foundational Paradigms
Pharmacology emerged as a distinct experimental science in the 19th century, separating from materia medica (descriptive study of medicinal substances) and physiology. 
carrington.edu +1

Receptor Theory and Occupancy Theory (Early 20th century): Drugs act by binding specific receptors (e.g., Langley, Ehrlich, Clark). This led to quantitative pharmacology, dose-response relationships, affinity/efficacy concepts, and structure-activity relationships (SAR).
Reductionist/Molecular Pharmacology (Mid-to-late 20th century): Focus on isolated targets, single-drug/single-target ("magic bullet") design, biochemical pathways, and molecular mechanisms. Dominated by high-throughput screening, genomics, and target-based drug discovery. This era emphasized selectivity and potency but faced high attrition due to overlooking systems-level effects. 
sciencedirect.com
Core enduring concepts include:
Pharmacokinetics (what the body does to the drug: ADME).
Pharmacodynamics (what the drug does to the body: mechanisms, dose-response).
Drug targets, interactions, metabolism, and elimination. 
bpspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com

Modern and Emerging Paradigms
Pharmacology has shifted toward integration, complexity, and translation due to limitations of pure reductionism (e.g., poor translation to complex diseases like neurodegeneration or cancer). 
pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

Systems Pharmacology and Network Pharmacology: A major paradigm shift viewing drugs in the context of biological networks, polypharmacology (multi-target effects), and system-wide interactions rather than single targets. Uses omics data, computational modeling, network analysis, and bioinformatics to predict effects, repurposing, and synergies. Particularly suited for complex, multifactorial diseases. 
ascpt.onlinelibrary.wiley.com +2
Translational Pharmacology: Bridges preclinical and clinical stages ("bench to bedside"). Emphasizes predictive animal models, biomarkers, model-informed drug development (MIDD), and addressing "valleys of death" in translation. Includes T1–T4 translational steps, with growing focus on real-world evidence (RWE). 
pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov +1
Quantitative and Model-Based Pharmacology: Integrates pharmacometrics, physiologically-based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling, quantitative systems pharmacology (QSP), and exposure-response relationships. Supports precision dosing and regulatory decisions.
Precision/Personalized Pharmacology: Incorporates pharmacogenomics, biomarkers, patient-specific factors (genetics, microbiome), and individualized therapy. Moves away from "one-size-fits-most."
AI, Computational, and Data-Driven Paradigms: AI/ML for de novo design, virtual screening, predictive toxicology, and AlphaFold-enabled structure prediction. Represents a potential major shift toward faster, cheaper discovery with open-source and collaborative platforms (e.g., ATOM consortium). 
digital-science.com +1
Modular and Multi-Target Paradigms: Drugs as modules affecting functional networks; includes PROTACs, ADCs, and combination therapies. 
tandfonline.com

Paradigm Shifts in Drug Discovery Strategies
Drug discovery has evolved through:
Natural products → Synthetic chemistry → Target-based HTS → Phenotypic screening → Systems/AI-driven approaches. 
facebook.com
Challenges like high attrition have driven calls for more integrative, hypothesis-driven (rather than purely technology-driven) research. 
