Current Context and Outlook
Paradigm shifts are "the normal state" in pharmacology, reflecting its integrative nature. 
pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

The field balances reductionist precision with holistic systems understanding, accelerated by AI, omics, and advanced modalities (e.g., gene/RNA therapies, radiopharmaceuticals). Translational and systems paradigms dominate discourse today to improve success rates and address real-world disease complexity.
These paradigms are not mutually exclusive; modern pharmacology synthesizes them (e.g., AI-enhanced network pharmacology for precision therapies). For doctoral-level work or specific applications (e.g., in oncology or neuropharmacology), the choice of paradigm shapes methodology, from molecular assays to large-scale modeling. If you'd like deeper focus on one (e.g., network pharmacology methods or historical case studies), let me know!"

